Q5. Efficiency optimisation trade-off study:
A 50W, 100kHz buck converter (V_in=48V, V_out=12V, I_load=4.167A, D=0.25) is being optimised. Current design uses:
Option A MOSFET: R_DS(on)=15mΩ, Q_gd=20nC (fast but resistive)
Option B MOSFET: R_DS(on)=40mΩ, Q_gd=5nC (slow but low conduction loss)
Option C MOSFET: R_DS(on)=25mΩ, Q_gd=10nC (balanced)
For all options: I_gate=1A, V_in=48V, I_load=4.167A, D=0.25.
(a) For each MOSFET option: calculate conduction loss (I_SW_rms=I_load×√D) and switching loss (t_sw=Q_gd/I_gate, use P_sw=½×V_in×I_load×2×t_sw×f_s)
(b) Total MOSFET loss for each option
(c) Which MOSFET minimises total MOSFET loss at f_s=100kHz?
(d) Repeat the comparison at f_s=500kHz. Does the optimal choice change?
(e) Find the crossover frequency (approximately) at which Option A and Option B have equal total loss. This is the frequency below which Option A is better (lower conduction loss matters more) and above which Option B is better (lower switching loss matters more). This illustrates why converter switching frequency directly determines which MOSFET parameter is most important to optimise.
